\begin_layout Section
Slow Cookoff on Short Bounded Domains
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Slow Cookoff on Bounded Domains"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Take domain 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\left[0,L\right]$
\end_inset

 with heating at the left boundary using either a fixed temperature or a
 fixed heat flux boundary condition, as described in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "sec:Time Step and Boundary Conditions"

\end_inset

.
 If the heating phase of the cookoff process (described in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "sec:Background"

\end_inset

) takes time 
\begin_inset Formula $t^{*}$
\end_inset

, we require 
\begin_inset Formula $L\ll c_{0}\cdot t^{*}$
\end_inset

.
 This requirement is explained in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "sec:The-Isobaric-Cookoff-Technique"

\end_inset

.
 The domain is initially occupied by a reactive fluid with concentration
 1.
 The following technique accelerates the computation of the long heating
 phase.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Take the reactive thermal subsystem of the motionless reactive HPR model:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{subequations}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\frac{\partial\left(\rho J_{i}\right)}{\partial t}+\frac{\partial T}{\partial x_{i}} & =-\frac{\rho H_{i}}{\theta_{2}\left(\tau_{2}\right)}\\
\frac{\partial\left(\rho E\right)}{\partial t}+\frac{\partial q_{k}}{\partial x_{k}} & =0\\
\frac{\partial\left(\rho\lambda\right)}{\partial t} & =-\rho\lambda K\left(T\right)
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{subequations}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
E=\frac{p+\gamma p_{\infty}}{\left(\gamma-1\right)\rho}+\frac{\alpha^{2}}{2}\left\Vert \boldsymbol{J}\right\Vert ^{2}-Q_{c}\left(1-\lambda\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Dumbser2015"

\end_inset

 it is shown that the heat characteristic of this system has speed:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
c_{h}=\frac{\alpha}{\rho}\sqrt{\frac{T}{c_{v}}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is also demonstrated that around equilibrium (
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{v}=\boldsymbol{0}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $A=I$
\end_inset

, 
\series bold

\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{J}=\boldsymbol{0}$
\end_inset


\series default
), the largest eigenvalue of the full HPR system has the following magnitude:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\sqrt{\frac{C\rho+\sqrt{C^{2}-4\rho^{2}c_{h}^{2}\left(p+\frac{4}{3}c_{s}^{2}\right)}}{2\rho}},\quad C=c_{0}^{2}+c_{h}^{2}+\frac{4}{3}c_{s}^{2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For example, with the conditions 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho=1$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $p=1$
\end_inset

 and parameters 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{s}=1$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=1$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{v}=2.5$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma=1.4$
\end_inset

 (as featured in many of the numerical tests in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Dumbser2015"

\end_inset

), the heat characteristic has speed 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{h}=\sqrt{\frac{2}{5}}\approx0.632$
\end_inset

, and the largest eigenvalue of the full system is approximately 2.20.
 Thus, by the definition in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "sec:Time Step and Boundary Conditions"

\end_inset

, the time step used in an explicit solver for the reduced system will be
 around 3.5 times larger than that for the full system.
 In this study, it is proposed that in simulating slow cookoff, the thermal
 subsystem alone is solved (similarly to the method employed in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Mccallen2003"

\end_inset

).
 Unlike in the cited paper, however, the full reactive HPR system will be
 employed when the rate of the chemical reaction becomes appreciable (which,
 of course, will be open to interpretation), to capture the full dynamics
 of the violent combustion.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The reduced system is still hyperbolic but is now also conservative (unlike
 the full system).
 The ADER-WENO solver is no longer necessary, and a less expensive operator
 splitting scheme can be used, as described in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "sec:Operator-Splitting"

\end_inset

.
 The homogeneous subsystem is solved to first order, as higher-order accuracy
 is not needed here, owing to the smooth dynamics of the heating process.
\end_layout

