\begin_layout Subsection*
The Temperature Fix
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the original GFM, the entropy in the ghost region is fixed to the value
 of the interface cell in the real region (or, in the case of the isobaric
 fix, the second cell away from the interface).
 This was found to be inadequate in problems in which heat conduction across
 the material interface was desired, as the temperature in the ghost region
 then takes on an unrealistic value.
 Thus, when modeling problems involving intermaterial heat conduction with
 the HPR-RGFM, the density in the ghost region was fixed by a temperature
 requirement, rather than an entropy requirement.
 If the temperatures of materials 1 and 2 were 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{1},T_{2}$
\end_inset

 at the interface, the temperature in both of their ghost regions was set
 to 
\begin_inset Formula $T^{ghost}=\frac{T_{1}+T_{2}}{2}$
\end_inset

; a simple, intuitive choice to make.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $p^{ghost}=p^{*}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, when using a stiffened gas EOS, the ghost density for both fluids
 is:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\rho^{ghost}=\frac{p^{*}+p_{\infty}}{\left(\gamma-1\right)c_{v}T^{ghost}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $K=L$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $K=R$
\end_inset

.
 To ensure condition 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:determinantRestriction"

\end_inset

 is satisfied, the following transformation is required:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
A_{K}^{*}\rightarrow\left(\frac{\rho^{ghost}}{\rho_{K}^{*}}\right)^{\frac{1}{3}}A_{K}^{*}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To ensure that 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{1}^{ghost}=q_{1}^{*}$
\end_inset

 after the temperature fix, the following transformation is required:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
J_{K}^{*}\rightarrow\frac{T_{K}^{*}}{T^{ghost}}J_{K}^{*}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

